HAT is all humane glory ? but as a thought
VOT which dies in the birth, and is diffolved be-
fore it knowes muu ity. When my cogita-
tions mount with buſie ſteps unto the aiery
top ofgreatncffe, how Coone are they tired?
to fee with what a ſodain ſwinge it wheels
into the Weſt ; yet behold with what utam'd defires thefa
moving clods of earth yawne for it, and when obtaynd, what
does it doc, but whet their affections to freſh appetites?
What is honour, but another Haman? This day a compe-
nion with a King, on the morrow hanging on the gallowes
a Cory.cedian, enters the Itage, acts his part, and Exit.
What is promotion, but a ſudden joy full newes which kils
in the entertainment, and ticklesunto death? Violent riſings
have moſt violent failings.
What are riches? but ſummer birds, take wing when win-
ter comes ; painted grapes, more to fitisfie the eye then palat:
whole bloud doth not mutiny within them to ſee the pillars of
an once well formed State cracke into a diffolution, by thola
grand enemies to true happines, Avarice and Ambition? Thela
are they have cou celled murder, fline cur peace : neither in-

pers to another, bidding poor England make ready for her fi-
nerall, prepare her winding heet. Who can look up nourru-

(through cruellulage) bachloſt ſo much life bloud, that the

Niebe, dilioive to teares? yet bow doe we gepe for milery,

So, he Mercurius, whither now ? what running from
Wetminſter where is the newes your promiſe? what's done
about the lines of Communication? If any Citizens aske, rell
them that the walls of Jericho were rumbled downe with
Rammes bornes, and they'l know prefently what you mean.
The laſt week there iflued forth an Ordinance concerning
dip money, that it ſhould not paffe, it is good ideed against
the clipping of coyne to forbid it : but it had been better
badtbey publiſhed another for the clipping of conſciences
and commandit: for there are many, eſpecially Parliament
conſciences, larger then Hell, that they are able to quarter.
three Kingdomes is the very Saburbs, and yet leave roome e-
nough for Committes and Excifo men.
Committees (warme in every place, London, Weſtminſter,
Southwarke, for Mihtis, Exciſe, any thing every thing I was
going to ſay, that there is knavery in all Trades, but that I
knew the Parliament had ferved feven yeeres Apprentillaip.
Luke ap Harunny, ap Pillory, appcyſon-beard, ap brazen.
face, ap Walker, is no changeling, I muſt tell you : though his
head be braffe, yet his braynes are iron, which bee hangers
out Weekly into Journalls, baving firſt Chriſtned the faces of
them with a few tap-droppings of mylterious nonfenfe : his
laſt Friday es-pudding News, you ſhall fiode fild in the mouth
with a glorry morfell, thus he preſents his Reader : Where there
are il principles, they attrall obſcurity, plainele fixets pleafsere in
the sparkles of light. Speakes he this of himſelfe, or of ſome o-
Char? (DAUM now Oedipus, ſurely of himſelfe: for his pria-
ciples being ſo ill and his truth (the conſequence) fo obſcure,
it will trouble the beſt eyes with two payre of Spectacles to
tell whether he meanes yes or no : and he is ſo dazed with
the ſparkles of his owng Light, that he finds no plegfure but in
the downe right plaineneffe of bis owne lyes : yet bis M
derate intelligence, may be called a ſecond Revelation, onely
with this definition, that he ſpeakes greater Myſteries of the
two, in principio, and interprets himſelfe by way of recapi-
tulatior, in fine.
The Buckinghamhire Bumpkins are buzzing like bees -
bout the Parliament dore, whom they have accofted with a
molt admirable elaborate, zealous peece of Non-fence; but
I dare ſweate for Luketbst be bad no finger in it; amongſt
other particulars, there is one branch that yeelds this goodly
fruit, that they petition the Army may not disband, but with
all that they may not have quarter;wiS ever luchBeetleheads
bred in a Commonwealth ? to thinke that the Parliament
bas nothing elſe to doe, but to diſcant upon their loggeriſms?
Every foole can tell you of propofitions fent unto his ME-
jeſtie ; and now every Knave can ſpend his verdit on the
ifluc: the Parliament complained not long ſince that they
wanted money to pay the Army; it is a figne they have t-
nough now, that can ſpend it on ſuch frivolous errands for
they knew before they fent, that the King neither can
would affent unto them, unlelle they would have him be as
deeply perjur'd as themſelves; his anſwer indeed was gra-
cious, but his not figning, together with his approbation of
the Armies propoſals, rather then the Parliaments Propo
fitions, may to fome prove grei vous: bat there is craft in daw
bing, and time will tell this Riddle.
The Parliament bave beene much-abuſed lately, by fome,

(16)
Ordinances are dayly diſcharg'd by wbole volleyes, but
they give no great report, orely a flaſh and away; they are
like a man of clouts, more to terrific then endanger.
Newes, joyfull newes from Ireland, the renowned Inche
gwine hath bang'd Oxenle to fome tune; all that the Rogues
and Kernes con boaft of, is, That one payre of heels is worth
two payre of bands, and bad not the woods ſheltered their
retreat, 'tis thought this batrell bad ftruck a bargaine to a
Munſterian Conqueſt. Ta reſolved ſpirit, perills are but
enterludes: let us not thwart thoſe bigh deferis, thoſe happy
events, with felfe ends, finifter reaches, and domeſtick ſquab-
lings.
The Scots are very angry if any body car'd for't, fcoulding
aszealouſly in their Pulpits, as ever did Oyſter-Women at
Billingſgate: the Pope and his Pupils are but whifflers to Sir
John Presbyter, for raiſing fedition, and ſetting Kingdomes
together by the eares; it is rumor'd, they intend to ſee their
old friends ere long againe, and to eate a Chriſtmas Pye with
us, and 'tis not unlike, their ſtomacks being in a perpetuall
capacity, rather to eate then fight; there is a great deale of
money due unto 'em; by my confent, they ſhall bee payd in
nothing but clipt money, and crackt crownes."
As I told you before, ſo now I tell you againe, The Houles
are divided; and how they ſhould continue to the judicious
eye, is an ultra poffe: all the ſport is, now they have undone
the Kingdome, they are as faſt as they can undoing one ano.
ther; fo did the Seditions in fernalen, after they had expullt
the common enemy, lolt all their glory in the ruine of each
other.
Many Members are disjoyoted, fome expeld the Houſe;
the Logger-beaded Alderman will deliver no more fet Spec-
chestbere, nor ſweeten bis venerable feat with the con-
junction of his worſhipfull buttocks; it is a wonder that he
Aould act any thing that might render him worthy of an ac-
cufation, who when but a few Souldiers, the halt, the lame,
and the blind, came to demand their pay at the Parliament
dore, was ready to befhit himſelfe, and it is well knowns,
that the head quarters of his valour is in his teeth.
That which the Parliament could not intreat, Sir Thomas
Fairfax can command, the City hath a long time ſhuffled and
cut, it is expe&ted now they will deale faire, they are but
threeſcore thouſand pounds in arreares to the Army: pay this
ſcore filt, and then perbapps his Excellency will truſt a-
gaine.
There is little or nothing from the Affembly, orely they fit
Atill, for want of better imploymeat : Foure of them paſs'c
over the Pallace yard together the other day,their faces look't
to like foure Knaves in the Cards, that had they been in their
habit, there is none would have taken them for Fools: where
upon on takes his pen, and thus merrily writes;
Nought but Presbytery for current pafes,
Compounded of young Elders and old Alles:
Lovers of War they be, more then of Schoolas,
A mixed Government, fome Knades, fome Fooles.
The Presbyterians hang asthey goe; he that runs may eaſily
Spell their conſcience in their countenance, ſtigmatized in
thoſe two indelible characters of Coveton neffe and Pride.
Malter Peters that pragmaticall hedge-prieſt, comming
lately to the Towne, upon ſome motions of ſpirit, told his
Hoft, that he muſt make bold with his houſe for a Conventicle
on the morrow, which the good man granted, not knowing
in what roome he would take up his ſtanding ; but the Con-
gregation not appearing, he left a point or two of confola-
tion with his Land-Lady, and ſo departed.
You that be the grand Intelligencers of the Kingdome, there
is one Collonell Thomas Long, now in Dablin kindely com-
mends him to you all, and deſires you to remember him in
your Diurnals, when they ride hickney for Weſtminſter;
he now lyes in of a fore heele, which he got at the great
battell of Trime; will you let ſuch valour perilo in the bloom
J pray you therefore henceforwards to take notice of him;
for I can aſure you he is a very deſerving Gentlema.

(18)
Now are the Parliament upon ſettling the Kingdome, it is
already upon the lees: what is now to be done? O you that
have fate ſo long at the Helane of this our weather-beaten
State, if now you prove good Pilots, and bring us into the
fafe barbour of a long expected Peace, all the Bells in the
Kingdome ſhall ring round, and we will buye all Major Ge-
nerali Browns Wood piles to make bone-fires.
But why doe Ithus waſte time? I feele a fit of melanchol-
ly comming upon mee; God looke upon our forrowes, and
ſpend one aufpicious glance upon our qualing hopes: It is
no wonder if Heaven frowne upon us, and thrill his arrowed
plagues quite thorow the very bowels of us; when I recogi-
tate, that our fios out-ballance jadgements, I am utteny loft.
Except in hope: It is reported of Jeruſalem, that none of her
lovers did bewayle her, it was becauſe ſhe was adulterate :
ſuch are we, ſuch are our lovers : Englands Apoſtacy, is the
Worlds Ludibry:
One thing I muſt commend unto the courteous : Pity the
times, performe your Covenants, attend with patience, and
got from Earth, but looke from Heaven for a deliverance.
And so I rud,
Year loving Friend,
Mercurius Melancholions,
